{"title_page": "Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| synonyms        = Painful ophthalmoplegia \n| name            = Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome \n| image           = Tolosa-hunt ophtalmoplegia.jpg \n| caption         = Neuro-ophthalmologic examination showing [[ophthalmoplegia]] in a patient with '''Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome''', prior to treatment. The central image represents forward gaze, and each image around it represents gaze in that direction (for example, in the upper left image, the patient looks up and right; the left eye is unable to accomplish this movement). The examination shows [[Ptosis (eyelid)|ptosis]] of the left eyelid, [[exotropia]] (outward deviation) of the primary gaze of the left eye, and [[paresis]] (weakness) of the left [[Oculomotor nerve|third]], [[Trochlear nerve|fourth]] and [[Abducens nerve|sixth]] [[cranial nerves]]. \n| \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome''' ('''THS''') is a [[rare disease|rare disorder]] characterized by severe and unilateral [[headaches]] with orbital pain, along with weakness and paralysis ([[ophthalmoplegia]]) of certain eye muscles ([[extraocular muscle paresis|extraocular palsies]]).<ref name=wni>{{cite web |url=http://www.whonamedit.com/synd.cfm/3307.html |title=Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome | publisher=Who Named It |accessdate=2008-01-21 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the [[International Headache Society]] provided a definition of the diagnostic criteria which included [[granuloma]].<ref name=\"pmid16776691\">{{cite journal |vauthors=La Mantia L, Curone M, Rapoport AM, Bussone G |title=Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome: critical literature review based on IHS 2004 criteria |journal=[[Cephalalgia (journal)|Cephalalgia]] |volume=26 |issue=7 |pages=772\u201381 |year=2006 |pmid=16776691 |doi=10.1111/j.1468-2982.2006.01115.x }}</ref>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nSymptoms are usually limited to one side of the head, and in most cases the individual affected will experience intense, sharp pain and paralysis of muscles around the eye.<ref name=eMedicine><{{cite web |url=http://www.emedicine.com/neuro/topic373.htm |title= Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome | author=Danette C Taylor, DO | publisher=eMedicine |accessdate=2008-01-21 }}</ref> Symptoms may subside without medical intervention, yet recur without a noticeable pattern.<ref name=nord>{{cite web |url=http://www.rarediseases.org/search/rdbdetail_abstract.html?disname=Tolosa%20Hunt%20Syndrome |title= Tolosa Hunt Syndrome | publisher=National Organization for Rare Disorders, Inc. |accessdate=2008-01-21 |format= }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, affected individuals may experience paralysis of various facial nerves and drooping of the upper eyelid ([[ptosis (eyelid)|ptosis]]). Other signs include [[Diplopia|double vision]], [[fever]], chronic [[fatigue (medical)|fatigue]], [[Vertigo (medical)|vertigo]] or [[arthralgia]]. Occasionally the patient may present with a feeling of protrusion of one or both eyeballs ([[exophthalmos]]).<ref name=eMedicine/><ref name=nord/>\n==Causes==\nThe exact cause of THS is not known, but the disorder is thought to be, and often assumed to be, associated with inflammation of the areas behind the eyes ([[cavernous sinus]] and [[superior orbital fissure]]).\n\n==Diagnosis==\nTHS is usually diagnosed via exclusion, and as such a vast amount of laboratory tests are required to rule out other causes of the patient's symptoms.<ref name=eMedicine/> These tests include a [[complete blood count]], [[thyroid]] function tests and [[serum protein electrophoresis]].<ref name=eMedicine/> Studies of [[cerebrospinal fluid]] may also be beneficial in distinguishing between THS and conditions with similar signs and symptoms.<ref name=eMedicine/>\n\n[[MRI]] scans of the brain and [[orbit]] with and without contrast, [[magnetic resonance angiography]] or [[digital subtraction angiography]] and a [[CT scan]] of the brain and orbit with and without contrast may all be useful in detecting [[inflammation|inflammatory]] changes in the cavernous sinus, superior orbital fissure and/or orbital apex.<ref name=eMedicine/> Inflammatory change of the orbit on cross sectional imaging in the absence of cranial nerve palsy is described by the more benign and general nomenclature of [[orbital pseudotumor]].\n\nSometimes a [[biopsy]] may need to be obtained to confirm the diagnosis, as it is useful in ruling out a [[neoplasm]].<ref name=eMedicine/>\n\nDifferentials to consider when diagnosing THS include [[craniopharyngioma]], [[migraine]] and [[meningioma]].<ref name=eMedicine/>\n\n==Treatment==\nTreatment of THS includes immunosuppressives such as [[corticosteroids]] (often [[prednisolone]]) or steroid-sparing agents (such as [[methotrexate]] or [[azathioprine]]).<ref name=eMedicine/> \n\n[[Radiotherapy]] has also been proposed.<ref name=\"pmid15836581\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Foubert-Samier A, Sibon I, Maire JP, Tison F |title=Long-term cure of Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome after low-dose focal radiotherapy |journal=Headache |volume=45 |issue=4 |pages=389\u201391 |year=2005 |pmid=15836581 |doi=10.1111/j.1526-4610.2005.05077_5.x }}</ref>\n\n==Prognosis==\nThe prognosis of THS is usually considered good. Patients usually respond to corticosteroids, and spontaneous remission can occur, although movement of ocular muscles may remain damaged.<ref name=eMedicine/> Roughly 30\u201340% of patients who are treated for THS experience a [[relapse]].<ref name=eMedicine/>\n\n==Epidemiology==\nTHS is uncommon in both the [[United States]] and internationally. There is one recorded case in [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]].<ref name=eMedicine/> Both genders, male and female, are affected equally, and it typically occurs around the age of 60.<ref name=wni/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = 31164\n| ICD10           = G44.850\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|378.55}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = neuro\n| eMedicineTopic  = 373\n| MeshID          = D020333\n| Orphanet        = 64686\n| SNOMED CT       = 95794005\n}}\n{{commons category|Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome}}\n\n{{Headache}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tolosa-Hunt syndrome}}\n[[Category:Neurological disorders]]\n[[Category:Syndromes affecting the eyes]]\n[[Category:Abducens nerve]]\n[[Category:Rare diseases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| synonyms        = Painful ophthalmoplegia \n| name            = Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome \n| image           = Tolosa-hunt ophtalmoplegia.jpg \n| caption         = Neuro-ophthalmologic examination showing [[ophthalmoplegia]] in a patient with '''Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome''', prior to treatment. The central image represents forward gaze, and each image around it represents gaze in that direction (for example, in the upper left image, the patient looks up and right; the left eye is unable to accomplish this movement). The examination shows [[Ptosis (eyelid)|ptosis]] of the left eyelid, [[exotropia]] (outward deviation) of the primary gaze of the left eye, and [[paresis]] (weakness) of the left [[Oculomotor nerve|third]], [[Trochlear nerve|fourth]] and [[Abducens nerve|sixth]] [[cranial nerves]]. \n| \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome''' ('''THS''') is a [[rare disease|rare disorder]] characterized by severe and unilateral [[headaches]] with orbital pain, along with weakness and paralysis ([[ophthalmoplegia]]) of certain eye muscles ([[extraocular muscle paresis|extraocular palsies]]).<ref name=wni>{{cite web |url=http://www.whonamedit.com/synd.cfm/3307.html |title=Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome | publisher=Who Named It |accessdate=2008-01-21 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the [[International Headache Society]] provided a definition of the diagnostic criteria which included [[granuloma]].<ref name=\"pmid16776691\">{{cite journal |vauthors=La Mantia L, Curone M, Rapoport AM, Bussone G |title=Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome: critical literature review based on IHS 2004 criteria |journal=[[Cephalalgia (journal)|Cephalalgia]] |volume=26 |issue=7 |pages=772\u201381 |year=2006 |pmid=16776691 |doi=10.1111/j.1468-2982.2006.01115.x }}</ref>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nSymptoms are usually limited to one side of the head, and in most cases the individual affected will experience intense, sharp pain and paralysis of muscles around the eye.<ref name=eMedicine><{{cite web |url=http://www.emedicine.com/neuro/topic373.htm |title= Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome | author=Danette C Taylor, DO | publisher=eMedicine |accessdate=2008-01-21 }}</ref> Symptoms may subside without medical intervention, yet recur without a noticeable pattern.<ref name=nord>{{cite web |url=http://www.rarediseases.org/search/rdbdetail_abstract.html?disname=Tolosa%20Hunt%20Syndrome |title= Tolosa Hunt Syndrome | publisher=National Organization for Rare Disorders, Inc. |accessdate=2008-01-21 |format= }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, affected individuals may experience paralysis of various facial nerves and drooping of the upper eyelid ([[ptosis (eyelid)|ptosis]]). Other signs include [[Diplopia|double vision]], [[fever]], chronic [[fatigue (medical)|fatigue]], [[Vertigo (medical)|vertigo]] or [[arthralgia]]. Occasionally the patient may present with a feeling of protrusion of one or both eyeballs ([[exophthalmos]]).<ref name=eMedicine/><ref name=nord/>\n==Causes==\nThe exact cause of THS is not known, but the disorder is thought to be, and often assumed to be, associated with inflammation of the areas behind the eyes ([[cavernous sinus]] and [[superior orbital fissure]]).\n\n==Diagnosis==\nTHS is usually diagnosed via exclusion, and as such a vast amount of laboratory tests are required to rule out other causes of the patient's symptoms.<ref name=eMedicine/> These tests include a [[complete blood count]], [[thyroid]] function tests and [[serum protein electrophoresis]].<ref name=eMedicine/> Studies of [[cerebrospinal fluid]] may also be beneficial in distinguishing between THS and conditions with similar signs and symptoms.<ref name=eMedicine/>\n\n[[MRI]] scans of the brain and [[orbit]] with and without contrast, [[magnetic resonance angiography]] or [[digital subtraction angiography]] and a [[CT scan]] of the brain and orbit with and without contrast may all be useful in detecting [[inflammation|inflammatory]] changes in the cavernous sinus, superior orbital fissure and/or orbital apex.<ref name=eMedicine/> Inflammatory change of the orbit on cross sectional imaging in the absence of cranial nerve palsy is described by the more benign and general nomenclature of [[orbital pseudotumor]].\n\nSometimes a [[biopsy]] may need to be obtained to confirm the diagnosis, as it is useful in ruling out a [[neoplasm]].<ref name=eMedicine/>\n\nDifferentials to consider when diagnosing THS include [[craniopharyngioma]], [[migraine]] and [[meningioma]].<ref name=eMedicine/>\n\n==Treatment==\nTreatment of THS includes immunosuppressives such as [[corticosteroids]] (often [[prednisolone]]) or steroid-sparing agents (such as [[methotrexate]] or [[azathioprine]]).<ref name=eMedicine/> \n\n[[Radiotherapy]] has also been proposed.<ref name=\"pmid15836581\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Foubert-Samier A, Sibon I, Maire JP, Tison F |title=Long-term cure of Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome after low-dose focal radiotherapy |journal=Headache |volume=45 |issue=4 |pages=389\u201391 |year=2005 |pmid=15836581 |doi=10.1111/j.1526-4610.2005.05077_5.x }}</ref>\n\n==Prognosis==\nThe prognosis of THS is usually considered good. Patients usually respond to corticosteroids, and spontaneous remission can occur, although movement of ocular muscles may remain damaged.<ref name=eMedicine/> Roughly 30\u201340% of patients who are treated for THS experience a [[relapse]].<ref name=eMedicine/>\n\n==Epidemiology==\nTHS is uncommon in both the [[United States]] and internationally. There is one recorded case in [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]].<ref name=eMedicine/> Both genders, male and female, are affected equally, and it typically occurs around the age of 60.<ref name=wni/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|   DiseasesDB     = 31164 \n|   ICD10          = G44.850 \n|   ICD9           = {{ICD9|378.55}} \n|   ICDO           = \n|   OMIM           = \n|   MedlinePlus    = \n|   eMedicineSubj  = neuro \n|   eMedicineTopic = 373 \n|   MeshID         = D020333 \n|   Orphanet       = 64686\n}}\n{{commons category|Tolosa\u2013Hunt syndrome}}\n\n{{Headache}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tolosa-Hunt syndrome}}\n[[Category:Neurological disorders]]\n[[Category:Syndromes affecting the eyes]]\n[[Category:Abducens nerve]]\n[[Category:Rare diseases]]\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tolosa%E2%80%93Hunt_syndrome"}
{"title_page": "PFC Akademik Sofia", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname    = Akademik\n| image       = Akademik sofia logo new.png\n| fullname    = \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0441\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d \u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043a \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f<br>{{nowrap|{{small|(Professional football club Akademik Sofia)}}}}\n| nickname    = ''\u0421\u0442\u0443\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435'' (The Students)\n| founded     = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1947}} <br/> (Refunded) {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|2013}}<br/>(as ''FC Akademik 1947'')\n| dissolved   = \n| ground      = [[Akademik Stadium]],<br>[[Sofia]]\n| capacity    = 10,000\n| chairman    = Atanas Ivanov\n| manager     =  Sasho Borisov\n| league      = A Regional Group (South) - Sofia (capital) \n| season      = 2018-19\n| position    = A Regional Group (South) - Sofia (capital), 4th\n| pattern_la1 = _whiteborder|pattern_b1=|pattern_ra1=_whiteborder\n| leftarm1    = 77BBFF|body1=77BBFF|rightarm1=77BBFF|shorts1=1A2D69|socks1=77BBFF\n| pattern_la2 = |pattern_b2=|pattern_ra2=\n| leftarm2    = FFD800|body2=FFD800|rightarm2=FFD800|shorts2=1A2D69|socks2=FFD800\n}}\n'''Akademik''' ({{lang-bg|\u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043a}}) is a [[Bulgaria]]n [[Football (soccer)|football]] club from [[Sofia]], which currently plays in Bulgaria's fourth tier, the regional league of Sofia. The team's [[Akademik Stadium|stadium]] is located in the [[Slatina, Bulgaria|Slatina]] municipality of Sofia and its capacity is 10,000.\n\nAkademik debuted in [[A PFG]] in 1949 and would quickly establish themselves as a top-flight team in Bulgarian football from then on. The team became one of the top Bulgarian teams in the 1950s and 1970s, especially in the domestic and European Cup competitions, having been crowned [[Balkans Cup]] champions. Akademik's last appearance in the Bulgarian First League came in 2010, after which the team experienced financial problems and folded after the 2011-12 season. It was refounded in 2013, starting from the fourth division.\n\n==History==\nAkademik was founded in the 1947, by [[Sofia University]] (the oldest higher education institution in Bulgaria, founded on 1 October 1888) students as a football club. A two years later, Akademik were promoted for the first time to [[Bulgarian A Football Group|Bulgarian A Group]]. The [[1950 A Group|1950 season]] in the domestic league was very successful for the team, which finished 3rd in the top division. In the next campaign Akademik finished fourth and reached the final of [[Bulgarian Cup]], losing 0\u20131 to [[PFC CSKA Sofia|CSKA Sofia]]. In 1952 the club's form dropped, however, and they were relegated to [[B PFG]] finishing before the last [[PFC Spartak 1918|Spartak Varna]]. In 1963\u201364 season they won a second promotion to the top division by winning the B PFG. However, the next year they were relegated again.\n\nThe third promotion to A Group in 1969 marked the beginning of Akademik's golden age. From 1969 to 1979 they spent their longest ever period in the top division. In 1974 Akademik won first international throphy, beating [[FK Vardar|Vardar Skopje]] 2\u20130 on aggregate in the final of [[Balkans Cup]]. In the 1975\u201376 season the team finished 3rd in the domestic league and qualified for first time in [[UEFA Cup]]. At the European level Akademik made a memorable appearance in the second round against Italian giants [[A.C. Milan]], winning 4\u20133 at home on 20 October 1976. Before reaching the second round of the football competition, the Students eliminated the Czech [[Slavia Prague]] respectively. In this period two players from Akademik have played for the Bulgarian national squad at a[[FIFA World Cup]]: Ivan Dimitrov in [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]] and [[Mladen Vasilev]] in [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]].\n[[File:Akademik 2010.jpg|thumb|280px|right|2009\u201310 team, which won promotion to [[Bulgarian A Football Group|A Group]].]]\nIn the 1978\u201379 season Akademik won just six games in the campaign and were relegated. In the next season the team won promotion back to the top division, scoring 100 goals in the campaign. In 1981 the Students qualified for second time in [[UEFA Cup]], where they lost 1\u20133 on aggregate in the first round against [[1. FC Kaiserslautern]]. In the same 1981\u201382 season Akademik again relegated. From 1982 to 2010 they spent their longest ever period out of the top division.\n\nAfter 28 years in the lowers divisions of Bulgarian football, in 2009\u201310 Akademik finished 2nd in [[B PFG]] and the club managed to participate in the play-off for promotion in the [[A PFG]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Livescore|title=Akademik's 2009\u201310 results and fixtures|url=http://www.livescore.cz/team.php?teamid=187879|accessdate=4 January 2011}}</ref> On May 23, 2010, Akademik surprisingly won the play-off against [[PFC Nesebar|Nesebar]] with a result of 2:1 and finally qualified again for the top division.\n\nDuring the summer of 2010, Akademik announced that they will play their home games at the [[Slavia Stadium]], home of [[Slavia Sofia]], instead of their usual stadium, [[Akademik Stadium]]. This was because Akademik Stadium did not obtain approval from the [[Bulgarian Football Union|BFU]]. The return to the elite proved to be hard. Academic won only 5 games, and drew 5 more, out of 30 games in total. This only earned the team 20 points, which was 5 points below [[Vidima-Rakovski Sevlievo]], who qualified for the relegation playoffs. Despite the bad results, Akademik was above the relegation zone up until round 25 of the season. The biggest highlight for Akademik was probably when the team managed to draw 1-1 against [[CSKA Sofia]], the most decorated team in Bulgarian football. However, Akademik were relegated from [[A PFG]] at the end of the 2010/2011 season after finishing in 15th place. The team finished 7th in the [[2011-12 B Group]], meaning they were relegated to the [[V AFG]]. However, the team decided not to play the following season, citing financial problems. The team was subsequently dissolved in 2012, only remaining active at youth levels.\n\n===League positions===\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:900 height:60\nPlotArea  = left:10 right:10 bottom:30 top:10\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/07/2007 till:01/07/2020\nScaleMajor = unit:year increment:1 start:2008\nColors =\n  id:bl1  value:rgb(0.5,0.8,0.5)\n  id:bl2  value:rgb(0.9,0.9,0.3)\n  id:rs  value:rgb(0.8,0.6,0.6)\n  id:rn  value:rgb(0.9,0.1,0.1)\n\nPlotData=\n  bar:Position width:16 color:white align:center\n  from:01/07/2007 till:01/07/2008  shift:(0,-4) text:10\n  from:01/07/2008 till:01/07/2009  shift:(0,-4) text:8\n  from:01/07/2009 till:01/07/2010  shift:(0,-4) text:2\n  from:01/07/2007 till:01/07/2010  color:white  shift:(0,14)  text: \"[[Bulgarian B Football Group|B Group]]\"\n  from:01/07/2010 till:01/07/2011  shift:(0,-4) text:15\n  from:01/07/2010 till:01/07/2011  color:green  shift:(0,14)  text: \"[[Bulgarian A Football Group|A Group]]\"\n  from:01/07/2011 till:01/07/2012  shift:(0,-4) text:7\n  from:01/07/2011 till:01/07/2012  color:white  shift:(0,14)  text: \"[[Bulgarian B Football Group|B Group]]\"\n  from:01/07/2012 till:01/07/2013  color:black  shift:(0,14)  text: Dissolved\n  from:01/07/2013 till:01/07/2014  shift:(0,-4) text:5\n  from:01/07/2014 till:01/07/2015  shift:(0,-4) text:2\n  from:01/07/2015 till:01/07/2016  shift:(0,-4) text:7\n  from:01/07/2016 till:01/07/2017  shift:(0,-4) text:6\n  from:01/07/2017 till:01/07/2018  shift:(0,-4) text:5\n  from:01/07/2018 till:01/07/2019  shift:(0,-4) text:4\n  from:01/07/2019 till:01/07/2020  shift:(0,-4) text:\n  from:01/07/2013 till:01/07/2020  color:yellow  shift:(0,14)  text: [[Regional Amateur Football Groups (Bulgaria)|Regional]]\n</timeline>\n\n==Honours==\n===Domestic===\n'''[[Bulgarian A Football Group|A Group]]:'''\n* [[Image:Bronze medal icon.svg|15px]] Third place (2): [[1950 A Group|1950]], [[1975\u201376 A Group|1975\u201376]]\n\n'''[[Bulgarian B Professional Football Group|B Group]]:'''\n* [[Image:Gold medal icon.svg|15px]] '''Winners (2):''' 1963\u201364, 1979\u201380\n* [[Image:Silver medal icon.svg|15px]] Runners-up (1): [[2009\u201310 B Group|2009\u201310]]\n\n'''[[Bulgarian Cup]]:'''\n* [[Image:Silver medal icon.svg|15px]] Runners-up (1): [[1951 Bulgarian Cup Final|1951]]\n\n===European===\n;'''[[Balkans Cup]]'''\n* Winners: [[Balkans Cup|1974]]\n;'''[[UEFA Cup]]'''\n* 1/16 finalist: [[1976\u201377 UEFA Cup|1976\u201377]]\n\n===European cup history=== \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Season\n! Competition\n! Round\n! Country\n! Club\n! Home\n! Away\n! Aggregate\n|-\n|[[UEFA Cup 1976-77|1976\u201377]]\n|[[UEFA Cup]]\n|1\n|{{flagicon|Czech Republic}}\n|[[Slavia Prague]]\n|3\u20130\n|0\u20132\n|3\u20132\n|-\n|\n|\n|2\n|{{flagicon|Italy}}\n|[[A.C. Milan]]\n|4\u20133\n|0\u20132\n|4\u20135\n|-\n|[[UEFA Cup 1981-82|1981\u201382]]\n|[[UEFA Cup]]\n|1\n|{{flagicon|Germany}}\n|[[1. FC Kaiserslautern]]\n|0\u20131\n|1\u20132\n|1\u20133<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=1976/clubs/club=63051/history/index.html PFC Akademik Sofia UEFA History] ''UEFA.com'' Retrieved 28 Mar 2016.</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notable stats==\n[[File:\u041c\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043d \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0435\u0432 00511.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Mladen Vasilev]], the club's top scorer in the league]]\n{|\n|valign=\"top\" width=33%|\n\n*'''Most appearances for the club in [[A PFG]]'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n!#!!Name!!Apps\n|-\n|1||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Iliya Chalev]]||253\n|-\n|2||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Yuliyan Ivanov]]||209\n|-\n|=||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Mladen Vasilev]]||209\n|-\n|4||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Bogomil Simov]]||177\n|-\n|5||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Boris Angelov]]||172\n|-\n|6||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Lozan Lozanov]]||156\n|-\n|7||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Stefan Parvanov]]||154\n|-\n|8||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Milen Goranov]]||147\n|-\n|9||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Petar Zafirov]]||141\n|-\n|10||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Todor Paunov]]||132\n|-\n|}\n| valign = \"top\" width=33%|\n\n*'''Most goals for the club in [[A PFG]]'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n!#!!Name!!Gls\n|-\n|1||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Mladen Vasilev]]||68\n|-\n|2||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Milen Goranov]]||38\n|-\n|3||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Alyosha Dimitrov]]||33\n|-\n|4||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Bogomil Simov]]||30\n|-\n|5||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Ivan Trendafilov]]||26\n|-\n|6||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Vasil Spasov (footballer)|Vasil Spasov]]||21\n|-\n|7||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Yordan Nikolov]]||18\n|-\n|8||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Hristo Konakov]]||16\n|-\n|9||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Kiril Milanov]]||16\n|-\n|10||{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Plamen Tsvetkov]]||15\n|-\n|}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.akademik-sofia.com  Official Fan site of Akademik Sofia]\n* [http://akademik-sofia.com/forum.com/  Official Fan forum of Akademik Sofia]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/AKADEMIK.Sofia.AKADEMIK  page in Facebook]\n\n{{BG A PFG}}\n{{Football in Bulgaria}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akademik Sofia}}\n[[Category:Football clubs in Sofia]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1947]]\n[[Category:1947 establishments in Bulgaria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname    = Akademik\n| image       = Akademik sofia logo new.png\n| fullname    = \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0441\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d \u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043a \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f<br>{{nowrap|{{small|(Professional football club Akademik Sofia)}}}}\n| nickname    = ''\u0421\u0442\u0443\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435'' (The Students)\n| founded     = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1947}} <br/> (Refunded) {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|2013}}<br/>(as ''FC Akademik 1947'')\n| dissolved   = \n| ground      = [[Akademik Stadium]],<br>[[Sofia]]\n| capacity    = 10,000\n| chairman    = Atanas Ivanov\n| manager     =  Sasho Borisov\n| league      = A Regional Group (South) - Sofia (capital) \n| season      = 2018-19\n| position    = A Regional Group (South) - Sofia (capital), 4th\n| pattern_la1 = _whiteborder|pattern_b1=|pattern_ra1=_whiteborder\n| leftarm1    = 77BBFF|body1=77BBFF|rightarm1=77BBFF|shorts1=1A2D69|socks1=77BBFF\n| pattern_la2 = |pattern_b2=|pattern_ra2=\n| leftarm2    = FFD800|body2=FFD800|rightarm2=FFD800|shorts2=1A2D69|socks2=FFD800\n}}\n'''Akademik''' ({{lang-bg|\u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043a}}) is a [[Bulgaria]]n [[Football (soccer)|football]] club from [[Sofia]], which currently plays in Bulgaria's fourth tier, the regional league of Sofia. The team's [[Akademik Stadium|stadium]] is located in the [[Slatina, Bulgaria|Slatina]] municipality of Sofia and its capacity is 10,000.\n\nAkademik debuted in [[A PFG]] in 1949 and would quickly establish themselves as a top-flight team in Bulgarian football from then on. The team became one of the top Bulgarian teams in the 1950s and 1970s, especially in the domestic and European Cup competitions, having been crowned [[Balkans Cup]] champions. Akademik's last appearance in the Bulgarian First League came in 2010, after which the team experienced financial problems and folded after the 2011-12 season. It was refounded in 2013, starting from the fourth division.\n\n==History==\nAkademik was founded in the 1947, by [[Sofia University]] (the oldest higher education institution in Bulgaria, founded on 1 October 1888) students as a football club. A two years later, Akademik were promoted for the first time to [[Bulgarian A Football Group|Bulgarian A Group]]. The [[1950 A Group|1950 season]] in the domestic league was very successful for the team, which finished 3rd in the top division. In the next campaign Akademik finished fourth and reached the final of [[Bulgarian Cup]], losing 0\u20131 to [[PFC CSKA Sofia|CSKA Sofia]]. In 1952 the club's form dropped, however, and they were relegated to [[B PFG]] finishing before the last [[PFC Spartak 1918|Spartak Varna]]. In 1963\u201364 season they won a second promotion to the top division by winning the B PFG. However, the next year they were relegated again.\n\nThe third promotion to A Group in 1969 marked the beginning of Akademik's golden age. From 1969 to 1979 they spent their longest ever period in the top division. In 1974 Akademik won first international throphy, beating [[FK Vardar|Vardar Skopje]] 2\u20130 on aggregate in the final of [[Balkans Cup]]. In the 1975\u201376 season the team finished 3rd in the domestic league and qualified for first time in [[UEFA Cup]]. At the European level Akademik made a memorable appearance in the second round against Italian giants [[A.C. Milan]], winning 4\u20133 at home on 20 October 1976. Before reaching the second round of the football competition, the Students eliminated the Czech [[Slavia Prague]] respectively. In this period two players from Akademik have played for the Bulgarian national squad at a[[FIFA World Cup]]: Ivan Dimitrov in [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]] and [[Mladen Vasilev]] in [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]].\n[[File:Akademik 2010.jpg|thumb|280px|right|2009\u201310 team, which won promotion to [[Bulgarian A Football Group|A Group]].]]\nIn the 1978\u201379 season Akademik won just six games in the campaign and were relegated. In the next season the team won promotion back to the top division, scoring 100 goals in the campaign. In 1981 the Students qualified for second time in [[UEFA Cup]], where they lost 1\u20133 on aggregate in the first round against [[1. FC Kaiserslautern]]. In the same 1981\u201382 season Akademik again relegated. From 1982 to 2010 they spent their longest ever period out of the top division.\n\nAfter 28 years in the lowers divisions of Bulgarian football, in 2009\u201310 Akademik finished 2nd in [[B PFG]] and the club managed to participate in the play-off for promotion in the [[A PFG]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Livescore|title=Akademik's 2009\u201310 results and fixtures|url=http://www.livescore.cz/team.php?teamid=187879|accessdate=4 January 2011}}</ref> On May 23, 2010, Akademik surprisingly won the play-off against [[PFC Nesebar|Nesebar]] with a result of 2:1 and finally qualified again for the top division.\n\nDuring the summer of 2010, Akademik announced that they will play their home games at the [[Slavia Stadium]], home of [[Slavia Sofia]], instead of their usual stadium, [[Akademik Stadium]]. This was because Akademik Stadium did not obtain approval from the [[Bulgarian Football Union|BFU]]. The return to the elite proved to be hard. Academic won only 5 games, and drew 5 more, out of 30 games in total. This only earned the team 20 points, which was 5 points below [[Vidima-Rakovski Sevlievo]], who qualified for the relegation playoffs. Despite the bad results, Akademik was above the relegation zone up until round 25 of the season. The biggest highlight for Akademik was probably when the team managed to draw 1-1 against [[CSKA Sofia]], the most decorated team in Bulgarian football. However, Akademik were relegated from [[A PFG]] at the end of the 2010/2011 season after finishing in 15th place. The team finished 7th in the [[2011-12 B Group]], meaning they were relegated to the [[V AFG]]. However, the team decided not to play the following season, citing financial problems. The team was subsequently dissolved in 2012, only remaining active at youth levels.\n\n===League positions===\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:900 height:60\nPlotArea  = left:10 right:10 bottom:30 top:10\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/07/2007 till:01/07/2020\nScaleMajor = unit:year increment:1 start:2008\nColors =\n  id:bl1  value:rgb(0.5,0.8,0.5)\n  id:bl2  value:rgb(0.9,0.9,0.3)\n  id:rs  value:rgb(0.8,0.6,0.6)\n  id:rn  value:rgb(0.9,0.1,0.1)\n\nPlotData=\n  bar:Position width:16 color:white align:center\n  from:01/07/2007 till:01/07/2008  shift:(0,-4) text:10\n  from:01/07/2008 till:01/07/2009  shift:(0,-4) text:8\n  from:01/07/2009 till:01/07/2010  shift:(0,-4) text:2\n  from:01/07/2007 till:01/07/2010  color:white  shift:(0,14)  text: \"[[Bulgarian B Football Group|B Group]]\"\n  from:01/07/2010 till:01/07/2011  shift:(0,-4) text:15\n  from:01/07/2010 till:01/07/2011  color:green  shift:(0,14)  text: \"[[Bulgarian A Football Group|A Group]]\"\n  from:01/07/2011 till:01/07/2012  shift:(0,-4) text:7\n  from:01/07/2011 till:01/07/2012  color:white  shift:(0,14)  text: \"[[Bulgarian B Football Group|B Group]]\"\n  from:01/07/2012 till:01/07/2013  color:black  shift:(0,14)  text: Dissolved\n  from:01/07/2013 till:01/07/2014  shift:(0,-4) text:5\n  from:01/07/2014 till:01/07/2015  shift:(0,-4) text:2\n  from:01/07/2015 till:01/07/2016  shift:(0,-4) text:7\n  from:01/07/2016 till:01/07/2017  shift:(0,-4) text:6\n  from:01/07/2017 till:01/07/2018  shift:(0,-4) text:5\n  from:01/07/2018 till:01/07/2019  shift:(0,-4) text:4\n  from:01/07/2019 till:01/07/2020  shift:(0,-4) text:\n  from:01/07/2013 till:01/07/2020  color:yellow  shift:(0,14)  text: [[Regional Amateur Football Groups (Bulgaria)|Regional]]\n</timeline>\n\n==Honours==\n===Domestic===\n;'''[[Bulgarian A Football Group|A Group]]:'''\n* Third place (2): [[1950 A Group|1950]], [[1975\u201376 A Group|1975\u201376]]\n;'''[[Bulgarian B Professional Football Group|B Group]]:'''\n* Champions: 1963\u201364, 1979\u201380\n* Runners-up: [[2009\u201310 B Group|2009\u201310]]\n;'''[[Bulgarian Cup]]:'''\n* Runners-up (1): [[1951 Bulgarian Cup Final|1951]]\n\n===European===\n;'''[[Balkans Cup]]'''\n* Winners: [[Balkans Cup|1974]]\n;'''[[UEFA Cup]]'''\n* 1/16 finalist: [[1976\u201377 UEFA Cup|1976\u201377]]\n\n===European cup history=== \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Season\n!